<DOCNO> AP900917-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a survey of more than 1000 fledgling teachers 
finds them full of optimism that they can make a difference but 
fearful that they are unprepared for problemplagued youngsters 
the poll of teachers entering classes for the first time this 
fall issued monday by metropolitan life insurance co found that 
99 percent believe that all children can learn and 83 percent said 
they were confident they can make a difference in pupils lives 
but 58 percent said they wish they had more practical training 
before entering the classroom twothirds said they believe all 
teachers should be required to take a national standardized test to 
prove their qualifications 
and 45 percent agreed that even the best teachers will have 
difficulty succeeding with more than twothirds of their students 
threefourths believe many children come to school with so many 
problems that its hard for them to become good students 
the survey was the eighth poll of teacher attitudes conducted by 
the insurance company since 1984 
what is most striking is the enormous idealism with which 
new teachers are approaching their jobs the survey concluded 
before getting caught up in the realities of the job they have a 
very strong faith in what children and they themselves can 
achieve 
sharply contrasting with that optimism a survey of more than 
21000 veteran teachers released two weeks ago by the carnegie 
foundation for the advancement of teaching found that 61 percent 
consider morale at their schools fair or poor it also found a 
majority souring on the progress of school reform 
i can almost guarantee that unless government and other 
institutions start solving the outofschool problems of kids and 
unless our schools change dramatically to support teaching and 
learning five years from now this idealistic and committed group 
of new teachers will be leaving the profession in droves said 
albert shanker president of the american federation of teachers 
reacting to the latest poll 
the 1002 teachers surveyed by met life were selected randomly 
from a list of this springs teacher college graduates compiled by 
the american association of colleges for teacher education 
the survey was conducted by telephone in july and august by 
louis harris and associates inc it had a margin of sampling error 
of plus or minus three percentage points 
met life said it plans to poll the same group next spring to 
determine their attitudes after a year of classroom experience 
keith geiger president of the national education association 
the nations largest teacher union said the survey pointed up the 
need for all prospective teachers to gain classroom experience 
working with a mentor teacher 
he also called it disturbing that one out of five new teachers 
surveyed felt unprepared to teach students of different ethnic 
backgrounds 
 
editors note copies of the survey will be available later 
this month for free by writing to metropolitan life insurance co 
the american teacher survey po box 807 madison square station 
ew york ny 101590807 
</TEXT>
