<DOCNO> AP900917-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the 265th quartermaster detachment of the south 
carolina national guard is one of the reserve units called up for 
operation desert shield national writer fred bayles followed the 
14 guardsmen as they prepared for deployment and he was with them 
aboard the sandbox express 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
welcome aboard gentlemen 
said the air force loadmaster youll be flying freedom bird to 
the worlds largest beach without water 
the joke didnt register with the men of the 265th quartermaster 
detachment after a night of delays they just wanted to get on the 
c141 and sleep the expected 19 hours it would take to fly from 
georgia to saudi arabia 
but sleep would not be easy to come by this night for the south 
carolina national guard unit 
the hold of the big cargo plane was packed there was a scant 
two feet between the units four pickup trucks and the row of red 
web seats along the side of the plane 
the 14 men couldnt stretch their legs they couldnt lie down 
they couldnt read in the dim gloom of the cargo hold and they 
couldnt stay warm 
as the plane climbed to 37000 feet the temperature in the hold 
dropped to the low 60s the men rolled down the sleeves of their 
desert uniforms buttoned up their collars and shivered through the 
long night 
the only way you can do it is stand up for a while to get warm 
and then hope you can fall asleep said sgt hullie cohen who 
served in the air force before joining the guard 
the water purification unit from allendale sc deployed for 
saudi arabia late friday after 16 days of training at fort stewart 
ga boarded the plane just before midnight their m16s were on 
their shoulders and they carried white plastic bags with water 
rations and a toiletry bag containing toothbrush toothpaste 
razors shaving cream sunscreen bug spray skin conditioner lip 
balm eye drops and deodorant 
this is good enough for a vacation said sgt john williams 
but the next nine hours were no vacation 
the plane the name sandbox express stenciled on its side 
looked huge on the floodlit runway but once aboard space was a 
premium 
the web seats dug into the men as they tried to get comfortable 
some used their softsided canteens as pillows conversation was 
impossible the engines roar was hardly muted by the yellow foam 
plugs sticking out of each mans ears 
riding in the windowless hold was like cruising through the 
ocean in the belly of a whale 
the plane stopped at torrejon air base near madrid for fuel and 
a fresh crew giving the 265th three hours to wash up in the 
crowded bathroom send postcards home and watch a clint eastwood 
movie on a big screen television set up in a hanger 
spc mark rooker 20 the youngest member of the unit spent his 
time staring at the scenery rooker hasnt traveled much and he 
was fascinated by the flat landscape 
id like to come back here someday he said 
back on the plane the men ate an air force box lunch of ham and 
cheese sandwiches and packaged spanish pastries some visited the 
cockpit crew as the plane passed from spanish to french air 
controllers over the mediterranean 
seven hours later the plane rolled to a stop at a saudi 
airport it was 3 am local time the men scrambled down the 
ladder in full combat gear carrying the south carolina state flag 
but the only one to greet them was a bored sergeant who led them 
past giant cargo planes and a road busy with truck traffic 
they stopped at an intersection where a half dozen men were busy 
filling sandbags in the glare of a trucks headlights 
the 265th watched a little stupefied from their long flight 
ok said sgt earnest deloach the jokes over lets go 
back home 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900917-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachev driven by the 
radicals who control the parliament of the largest soviet republic 
seems to have accepted their prescription for the gasping soviet 
economy capitalism 
the economys fall into depression was a major impetus but the 
final push came from russian president boris yeltsin who won 
approval for the drastic reforms in the russian parliament this 
week and forced gorbachevs hand 
yeltsin threatened to pursue his economic revolution in russia 
which contains half the soviet people and threequarters of the 
countrys land mass with or without gorbachevs support 
gorbachev went along 
the economic plan he distributed to the national parliament on 
friday 95 percent coincides with the russian plan russian 
deputy prime minister grigory yavlinsky told his parliament on 
saturday 
that is an exaggeration gorbachev rejected some key points and 
a parliamentary battle remains to be fought but the comment was a 
good indication that the russian radicals feel they have already 
won 
in the five years since he came to power proclaiming the need 
for reform gorbachev has tinkered with the communist system 
trying to fill the barren shelves of soviet stores 
now he has thrown his support behind an economic reform plan 
full of ideas that warm the hearts of capitalists and horrify 
diehard communists private land home ownership merit pay and 
profits 
it also contains the thorns of capitalism unemployment factory 
closings bankruptcies and rising prices in the first months of 
switching to a market economy the soviet union is likely to feel 
the full pain of these thorns 
gorbachev this week was defensive thumping his fist in 
parliament as he told soviet legislators such radical change would 
have been impossible earlier 
a year and a half ago we were just talking about pluralism 
he said referring to the soviet unions dramatic switch to 
multicandidate elections 
if he had heeded calls to change from a centrally planned to a 
market economy then gorbachev said do you think anything would 
have come of it thats nonsense 
we needed all that time to think about things otherwise 
there would have been such a tragedy such confusion in the 
country that we never could have escaped it he said 
now however the changes must come quickly gorbachev admitted 
the old structures are falling apart and the new ones are not 
yet formed he said there is no system in the true sense of 
the word 
his own economic reform plan says the country already has 
entered an economic depression with rising foreign debt and 
declining ability to pay the countrys international economic 
position the plan said is catastrophic 
as a result gorbachevs economic plan says the gradual 
transition to a market economy proposed by soviet prime minister 
nikolai ryzhkov would be too slow 
without urgent action we would be forced to choose between 
hyperinflation and direct seizure of cash from the population and 
enterprises the plan says 
ryzhkov went on national television saturday night to argue for 
his moderate approach to reform and to insist on retaining through 
1991 the rigid soviet bureaucracy that now runs the economy 
in arguing against the russian republics plan ryzhkov 
predicted it would lead to a 30 percent drop in the countrys 
standard of living 
but ryzhkovs plan which calls for dramatic price increases on 
jan 1 without fundamental structural changes is so unpopular that 
legislators have called for his resignation and about 50000 
muscovites demonstrated near red square in a cold rain sunday 
evening calling for ryzhkov to step down 
still remaining however is the battle over sections of the 
russian plan that would strip the central government of much of its 
power 
gorbachev has rejected that notion including calls to transform 
the country into an economic association like the european 
community his plan also deletes the russian call for republic laws 
to supersede national legislation 
neither gorbachev nor any other soviet politician has dared 
define the coming changes as capitalism 
instead officials say its time to kill off the dying 
authoritarian system and get on with what they call normal 
life 
 
editors note ann imse based in moscow has covered the 
soviet union for the associated press for two years 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

