<TEXT>
the house and senate have passed 
multimilliondollar bills establishing a civilian national 
service corps for young people but originators of the idea say 
the differing bills bear little resemblance to what they had in 
mind 
the committee picked up the ball but forgot to run rep 
dave mccurdy dokla one of the sponsors of national service 
said after the house passed its bill last thursday this bill is 
not national service 
nonetheless the 193 million bill the house approved on a voice 
vote after long debate bears the title national service act it now 
goes to a conference committee to work out differences with the 
senate which passed a 125 million bill that although less 
costly is more ambitious 
mccurdy and other original sponsors hope the final version will 
include a provision in the senates bill a 35 million 
demonstration program that will test their idea for linking 
national youth service with financial aid incentives 
its a plan that the house did not include the chairman of the 
house panel that wrote the bill retiring rep augustus hawkins 
dcalif opposed the idea and said his committee categorically 
rejects any linkage between service and student financial 
assistance 
the idea of a national service corps to encourage young people 
to do social works the nation otherwise couldnt afford has been 
bound up in political differences that go beyond pride of 
authorship 
president bush uttered the phrase a thousand points of light 
in his nominating speech and later refined it into a modest 25 
million plan to establish a clearinghouse for community service 
publicizing successful projects and encouraging new ones 
critics of that idea however concluded it would do little to 
actually support an organized effort harnessing the energy and time 
of young people to do constructive social or environmental work 
benefiting their communities 
moderate and conservative democrats who lead the democratic 
leadership council a group formed to counterbalance what they see 
as the more liberal national party organization proposed a more 
sweeping plan in january 1989 
their bill would have made student financial aid contingent on a 
fulltime stint in the military or in lowwage community service 
their bill would have phased out current forms of student aid in 
five years 
it would amount to a civilian gi bill a civilian program 
comparable to the benefits that encourage military service 
according to its sponsors led by mccurdy in the house and sens 
sam nunn dga and charles robb dva 
their plan met stiff resistance however and in the senate they 
settled for the scaledback pilot program participants could 
receive vouchers for use toward college a first home purchase or 
establishment of a small business worth 5000 for one yeas 
service 
i havent dropped my original thinking on the subject but i 
do think we ought to go slowly and determine what works nunn 
said 
critics who include liberal democrats as well as republicans 
said tying aid to service would penalize lowincome students while 
allowing the affluent to escape service obligations supporters 
however said lowincome students already have to work to 
supplement the meager support they get from existing student aid 
programs 
the houses bill provides grants to states and local school 
systems to encourage volunteer activity by young people and 
establishes youth conservation and service corps to do 
environmental and social projects 
sponsors of the democratic leadership councils plan say 
volunteerism is different and more limited in scope than what they 
have in mind they say hawkins committee with its ties to the 
establishment education and labor lobbies basically added money to 
existing programs and came up with little more than a traditional 
youth jobs program 
from our point of view the house really missed the point of 
national service said will marshall head of the progressive 
policy institute a democratic think tank that has pushed the idea 
the committee missed an opportunity for a dynamic fresh 
approach because members did not want to touch previously created 
sacred student aid programs mccurdy said 
but hawkins contends his bill will encourage volunteer work and 
responds to the same concerns that the president noted when he 
proposed his points of light initiative in his inaugural address 
this bill hawkins said is an attempt to make the concept 
of service more central to americans life and work 
