<TEXT>
ace feather detective roxie laybourne always 
gets her bird even when the evidence is a mere wisp of fluffy 
down 
from her cluttered aerie on the top floor of the national museum 
of natural history amid storage bins containing more than 600000 
specimens of stuffed birds the hawkeyed mrs laybourne reigns as 
the nations foremost authority on feathers 
give her a tuft of tail feathers and roxie nobody calls her 
mrs laybourne can tell whether they were plucked from an 
australian palm cockatoo a south african crowned plover or a 
caribbean coot 
criminal investigators once tapped her 46 years of expertise in 
a murder case involving a wife who shot her sleeping husband with a 
pistol wrapped in a feather pillow as a silencer 
roxie informed authorities that microscopic traces of down taken 
from the bullet lodged in the victims skull matched the feathers 
from the bulletpunctured pillow the new york times dubbed her 
miss marple of eiderdown 
roxie squints knowingly from behind her goldrimmed spectacles 
and whispers in a carolina drawl as thick as grits with ham gravy 
the fingerprint says you are it she confides feather 
evidence says you might be it the feather puts you at the scene of 
the crime 
roxies knack for unraveling the puzzles of plumage was 
discovered in 1960 when an eastern airlines turboprop hit a flock 
of starlings and crashed shortly after takeoff from boston killing 
62 people 
roxies identification of the mangled feathers scraped from the 
lockheed electras engines led to studies for the federal aviation 
administration and major aircraft engine manufacturers on designing 
safer birdproof planes 
a smithsonian research associate she roams the country 
testifying as an expert witness for the us fish and wildlife 
service against poachers smugglers of endangered birds and traders 
who sell contraband indian headdresses containing eagle feathers 
roxie also trained doug deedrick to become the fbi crime 
laboratorys expert on feather identification we met when he was 
specializing in hairs and fibers she said i asked him would 
you like to learn about feathers give me a call and come to my 
skinning class 
roxies admirers include james parrish a research ornithologist 
at brigham young university in provo utah who once sent roxie the 
bits and pieces of prey remains from a sharpshinned hawks nest in 
alabama 
she identified every one of them yellowbilled cuckoo 
northern mockingbird downy woodpecker and mourning dove parrish 
said shes the best shes irreplaceable i dont know anyone 
else in the world who can identify feather remains like she can 
kenneth goddard chief of the fish and wildlife services 
forensic laboratory in oregon says roxies abilities are amazing 
she can identify birds and feathers like they were her own 
children he said she can give their height weight sex even 
eye color its fascinating 
as a child in rural farmville nc roxie spent hours exploring 
the outdoors growing up in a small town i was always interested 
in anything that creeped and crawled she said she landed her 
first job after college at the north carolina state museum of 
natural history in raleigh in 1937 
her curiosity remains undimmed she is enthralled by the 
delicate lacework of the feathers under her microscope the pronged 
nodules on the quills the pigment cells that sometimes resemble 
tiny vienna sausages 
im learning new things every day thats what makes it 
exciting she said the more i delve into my feather stuff the 
more i see that needs explaining ill never be finished 
roxie recently got her first glimpse of a rubythroated 
hummingbirds feather magnified 1500 times under the lens of her 
scanning electron microscope 
it was so exciting she said it was like finding mysef 
in the middle of a great tropical forest id never seen before 
its as much excitement as id ever need 
