<TEXT>
the chairman of the national endowment for the 
arts expressed hope monday that the crisis will soon pass over 
federal support for controversial art with a senate proposal to let 
the courts decide whether works are obscene 
but chairman john e frohnmayer held fast at least for a while 
longer to his muchcriticized requirement that nea grant 
recipients sign a pledge not to use federal funds to produce art 
that might be considered obscene 
even though the pledge was prompted by a congressional obscenity 
ban that will expire sept 30 frohnmayer said he will keep the 
pledge until a federal court in new york issues a ruling on its 
constitutionality and congress decides whether to impose new 
antiobscenity restrictions on the endowment 
in any case the embattled nea chairman said there was zero 
truth to rumors that he may resign in the heat of battle over 
past endowment support for works that conservative critics have 
denounced as obscene and sacrilegious 
at a news conference at the national press club frohnmayer said 
he was heartened by two events last week 
one was a report by a bipartisan study commission that backed 
the endowment opposed antiobscenity curbs and called for reforms 
in the neas grant procedures 
the other was the emergence of a senate compromise that shifts 
the burden of deciding cases of obscene art from the nea to the 
courts 
both developments frohnmayer said give us hope that the 
crisis will soon pass 
the senate bill approved 151 last week by the labor and human 
resources committee provides a wise solution to a very thorny 
problem frohnmayer said 
the measure now headed for senate floor action would allow the 
endowment to get its money back if a grant recipient is convicted 
of creating works that violate obscenity or child pornography laws 
the guilty artist would be forbidden to receive further nea grants 
for at least three years 
we await the action of congress with the hope that clear 
thinking and cool heads prevail frohnmayer said 
frohnmayer outlines several internal reforms at the federal arts 
agency to make its grant procedures more responsive to the desires 
of the taxpaying public but he conceded that his reforms wont 
satisfy those who dont want an arts endowment 
