<TEXT>
like many parents with collegeage 
youngsters david and jean heard like to send care packages when 
their children are away from home 
but for the heard children the classroom is the persian gulf 
and their instruction could mean the difference between life and 
death 
since president bush ordered american troops to the middle east 
following the iraqi invasion of kuwait three of the heards 13 
sons and daughters have been caught up in the deployment 
one son is a marine in saudi arabia another a sailor is 
aboard the carrier independence in the persian gulf a daughter and 
her husband both in the military reserves remain in the united 
states but believe theyll be sent to the middle east 
mrs heard said she could not sit idle while she waited for news 
from abroad so she and her husband a retired marine started 
operation something from home 
their mission is to see that every serviceman and woman involved 
in operation desert shield gets something from home 
we have read over the years how military personnel never get a 
letter never get anything mrs heard said my god these are 
our children theyre all our sons and daughters and the least we 
can do is to get something to them 
what began from humble beginnings a few dollars and a couple 
of packages a week has grown into a nationwide effort all from 
the basement of the heards manassas home boxes are everywhere 
brimming with articles from chewing gum and crackers to toilet 
tissue and paperback novels 
nearly a dozen volunteers shuttle back and forth some operate 
the telephone others are assigned as shoppers who buy items to 
ship to the armed forces 
donations are pouring in as are letters of support a real 
estate company in the virgin islands sent a 50 check an envelope 
from an anonymous sender arrived last week with a 100 bill tucked 
inside 
aaron clark a fourthgrader from mount vernon ill created 
his own care package with a small box of cigars a roll of candy 
and a paperback novel he sent it to the heards with hopes that 
they would forward it to the troops 
other packages include razors lip balm liquid soap playing 
cards wooden dominoes and letters from school children all items 
being sent have been tested and shown to be desertproof 
mrs heard puts the items in the back window of her car for two 
days if they dont melt theyre included 
the packages arent sent to individuals by name but are sent to 
apo and fpo boxes that correspond with those of soldiers in the 
persian gulf region 
the packs are getting through david heard 55 got a thank you 
letter from a soldier of the 82nd airborne division who sent a 1 
contribution 
the care package service is going to be a real morale 
booster wrote another soldier in saudi arabia we are all over 
here for our country we will die for our country and if i die 
ill be proud within myself that i died for my country 
the letters they get from the recipients of the packages are 
reward enough for those involved in operation something from home 
thats worth 20 hours a day seven days a week mrs heard 
said when i get tired or discouraged i read those letters and 
im no longer tired i only wish there were 40 hours in a day 
in a way the effort is helping heal some old hurts left by the 
vietnam war she said the homespun packages are a lifeline for 
those deployed to the persian gulf and a way to show them that they 
are being supported back home 
do you remember when our people came back from vietnam mrs 
heard asked it was no longer an honor to wear a uniform they 
were spit at and rotten vegetables were thrown at them 
i am ashamed that i was one of those americans who didnt 
stand up and do anything she said i was a coward and i did 
nothing this country in 30 years has suffered so much there just 
didnt seem to be any unity and now if you read these letters 
god bless america warts and all mrs heard said 
 
editors note the mailing address for operation something from 
home is po box 264 manassas va 22110 
