<TEXT>
business inventories jumped 07 percent in 
july the biggest pileup in a year while sales slumped 05 
percent the government said monday causing some apprehension over 
the amount of goods held on shelves and back lots 
although the level of inventories is not recessionary robert 
brusca chief financial economist at nikko securities co 
international inc in new york said surging stockpiles are a 
danger sign 
when inventories rise faster than sales particularly when 
sales are in a lagging mode its reasonable to assume youre going 
to see cutbacks in manufacturing output he said that could 
result in growing unemployment 
the commerce department said inventories in july totaled a 
seasonally adjusted 8019 billion up from 7965 billion in june 
it was the biggest increase since a 08 percent gain in july 1989 
the june backlog had declined a revised 05 percent from the 
previous month rather than the 04 percent originally reported 
sales meanwhile dropped to a seasonally adjusted 5395 
billion down from 5424 billion a month earlier the june sales 
also were revised to a weaker 06 percent gain rather than the 10 
percent advance first reported 
cynthia latta an economist with drimcgrawhill in lexington 
mass noted that sales rose only on the retail level in july but 
pointed out that retail sales deteriorated in august falling 06 
percent according to a commerce department report last week 
and while retail sales increased 04 percent in july the gain 
was less than half of the 11 percent jump the previous month 
retail sales represent about half of all consumer spending which 
itself accounts for twothirds of the nations economic activity 
the combination of falling sales and rising inventories produced 
a 149 ratio of inventories to sales up from 147 in june and the 
same as mays 149 the ratio means it would take 149 months to 
exhaust the backlog of goods at the july sales pace 
neither brusca nor ms latta believe the ratio is dangerously 
high 
but with evidence that retail selling is weak and that output 
is falling to have inventories building is not a good sign for the 
economy brusca said 
all major business categories experienced gains in inventories 
manufacturing backlogs were up 07 percent to 3733 billion 
wholesalers posted a 05 percent gain to 1922 billion retailers 
registered a 08 percent advance to 2365 billion 
manufacturing sales meanwhile declined 08 percent to 2375 
billion while wholesalers posted a 10 percent drop to 1520 
billion retail sales totaled 1500 billion 
