<TEXT>
the bush administration spurred by events in 
the middle east set forth an ambitious negotiating schedule monday 
aimed at completing a comprehensive free trade agreement with 
oilrich mexico by the end of 1991 
administration officials said that president bush would formally 
submit to congress within the next few days a request for authority 
to negotiate an agreement dismantling barriers to the free flow of 
goods and investment between the two nations 
the administrations formal request starts a procedure in which 
congress has 60 legislative days a period expected to last until 
late spring to review the proposal if congress gives its assent 
which is considered likely then the administration can begin 
negotiations with mexico 
deputy us trade representative julius katz told members of the 
congressional joint economic committee that if negotiations begin 
in late spring he hoped to have an agreement wrapped up by the end 
of 1991 
that timetable would be significantly faster than the 18 months 
required to negotiate a freetrade agreement with canada 
katz told reporters later that us negotiators had learned a 
great deal from the uscanada free trade talks and believed that 
knowledge could be applied to speeding up a similar agreement with 
mexico 
administration officials have said that the middle east crisis 
has focused attention on americas trade relationship with mexico 
which has the eighth largest reserve of oil in the world 
the united states would like to work with mexico in accelerating 
oil production in mexico which currently stands at about 25 
million barrels of crude daily 
katz and other administration officials suggested monday that a 
free trade agreement with mexico would be a first step toward 
achieving the presidents goal of a hemispherewide free trade 
zone an achievement that katz said could be reached before the end 
of this decade 
members of the joint economic committee were generally 
supportive of the effort to remove trade barriers between the 
united states and other countries in latin america although sen 
paul sarbanes dmd questioned whether the administration had 
fully explored the impact on the us economy 
he questioned whether a free trade zone with mexico would 
encourage us manufacturers to move their operations to that 
country where the costs of labor were lower 
treasury under secretary david mulford said that while such an 
agreement would have a big impact on the mexican economy any 
effects on the us economy would likely be small given the 
relative size of the two economies mexicos total output is nly 4 
percent of americas 5 trillion annual economy 
mulford said that the administration was anxious to complete an 
agreement with mexico to reward mexican president carlos salinas de 
gortari for the freemarket economic reforms he has instituted in 
his country 
mexico is americas third largest trading partner with twoway 
trade totaling 51 billion last year 
