impoverished farm in a remote northcentral hamlet of poland and 
his education came at a technical school 
he has never learned to speak polish smoothly or any other 
language at all he is unpredictable and at times maddeningly 
ambiguous he has been photographed fishing in his underwear his 
suit collection was recently expanded by three but is still single 
digit 
in fact there have been suggestions among poles that walesa 
46 is not learned or cultivated enough to be president 
criticism that i do not know how to talk with presidents 
walesa once scoffed i have talked to them and they want to talk 
with me 
when walesa drifted to gdansk and took a job at the lenin 
shipyard in 1967 no one would imagined that a little more than two 
decades later one foreign leader after another would be making the 
pilgrimage to the baltic port to see him nato general secretary 
manfred woerner and former president reagan came on saturday alone 
walesas anticommunist activism can be traced to 1970 food 
price riots in which police killed some of his fellow workers he 
translated his growing furor into unquestioned authenticity 
he lost one job after another as his labor activism increased 
and was outside the strikebound shipyard when he made the famous 
leap that merged his destiny with polands future 
in his subsequent 10 years as solidaritys leader he has 
maneuvered through martial law imprisonment repression and 
finally the communist regimes overtures and its eventual 
downfall 
along the way there were eight children a nobel peace prize in 
1983 and enormous prestige at home and abroad his mustachioed face 
on countless magazine covers a noticeable paunch and graying hair 
but no dimming of his twinkling eyes and there was the 
incalculable satisfaction of seeing polands revolution sweep the 
east bloc 
yet the new solidarityled government walesa organized included 
no official role for himself pushing aside accusations he was a 
jealous demagogue walesa started to foment against his former 
allies now leading the country 
many inside and out of poland did not want to believe his 
message that solidaritys unified days were over and political 
parties had to develop but most have come to agree and elections 
are imminent 
now walesa must wait for democracys decision on whether he will 
add the presidency to his biography 
</TEXT>
