<TEXT>
a bill letting regulators tap banks and 
savings institutions to shore up the dwindling government deposit 
insurance funds passed the house on monday 
by a voice vote the house favored removing the legal ceiling on 
insurance premiums levied by the federal deposit insurance corp 
the senate is scheduled to consider the measure later this month 
congressional leaders the bush administration and the fdic are 
supporting passage before congress adjourns early next month 
fdic chairman l william seidman said the agency did not plan to 
use the new power immediately but wanted it to meet any unforeseen 
emergency 
we dont see at this time we are going to change the premiums 
again however its an uncertain world and we thought wed be 
better equipped to handle things if we had the flexibility he 
said in a telephone interview 
the house action comes a week after the general accounting 
office congress auditing agency warned that bank failures 
produced by a recession could wipe out the fund protecting bank 
deposits requiring a taxpayer bailout 
the fund protecting savings and loans has already been 
bankrupted as part of negotiations on the 1991 budget congress 
and the administration are considering financing a second 
installment of the rescue begun last year 
the insurance premium bill is aimed at avoiding a similar 
bailout for banks according to its sponsor rep henry b 
gonzalez dtexas chairman of the house banking committee it 
gives the fdic discretion to raise insurance premiums to whatever 
level it considers appropriate 
seidman has warned that the bank fund is under considerable 
stress and will probably experience its third consecutive loss 
this year as bank failures remain near a postdepression record 
that would bring fund reseves down to near 11 billion or 
between 50 cents and 60 cents for every 100 of insured deposits 
that is less than half the 125 reserve ratio considered safe 
the fdic insurance fund is teetering on the brink of 
insolvency warned rep frank annunzio dill chairman of the 
house banking financial institutions subcommittee 
in an attempt to bolster the fund the fdic later this month is 
expected to raise its 1991 bank premium from 12 cents per 100 of 
deposits to 195 cents it is the biggest increase allowed under 
current law 
gonzalez bill would scrap the 75 cent limit on annual 
increases and the 325 upper ceiling on the premium it would also 
remove provisions restricting the agency to raising the premium 
only once a year requiring instead that the fdic give 60 days 
notice of increases as needed 
rep chalmers wylie of ohio the senior republican on the 
banking committee said premiums may not have to be raised more 
than planned but said it would be irresponsible to taxpayers for 
congress not to give the fdic power to take swift action 
we are practicing an ounce of prevention before a pound of 
cure is needed he said 
kenneth guenther executive vice president of the independent 
bankers association of america said industry groups were not 
lobbying against gonzalez bill 
but he said bankers worried that the fasttrack procedure 
congress is using to adopt the measure is creating a false 
impression that there is an emergency in the banking system 
with the premium increase already planned the fdic will have an 
additional 6 billion next year to pay for bank failures he said 
</TEXT>
