<TEXT>
a california businessman pleaded guilty monday 
to conspiring to bribe two navy procurement officials by paying 
them more than 26000 to help his company obtain lucrative 
electronics contracts 
manuel r caldera 59 former chairman of amex systems inc of 
los angeles pleaded guilty to conspiracy to pay bribes and making 
an illegal payment to a public official 
together the charges carry a maximum sentence of seven years 
imprisonment and fines of 500000 
the guilty plea before us district judge claude m hilton in 
alexandria va marked the latest conviction in the governments 
investigation of pentagon procurement fraud 
thirtynine defense consultants procurement officials and 
contractors plus several companies have been convicted since the 
investigation known as operation ill wind became public more 
than two years ago 
caldera a mexicanamerican who was honored in 1983 by president 
reagan as a minority businessman admitted paying bribes to former 
navy procurement officials stuart e berlin and james d sampson 
between 1978 and 1985 
the two former officials who worked for the naval electronics 
system command in arlington va agreed to approve additional 
contract work for amex in return for the money according to court 
papers 
sampson who has not been charged and berlin who is serving a 
26month prison term for his guilty plea to unrelated charges are 
cooperating with the investigation 
the conspiracy charge to which caldera pleaded guilty listed 
payments of 26000 between 1982 and 1985 a statement of facts 
filed by prosecutors indicated payments totalled 34000 between 
1978 and 1985 
until 1984 amex was eligible to obtain government contracts 
without competing with other firms because it was a minorityowned 
business prosecutors said the minoritybusiness preference ended 
shortly before amex was sold to allied corp for 45 million 
hilton scheduled sentencing for nov 30 
</TEXT>
