<TEXT>
the test of any great role is in the different 
ways it can be performed and still be successful 
a fine example is now on view at broadways st james theater 
where the revival of gypsy has a new rose that quintessential 
stage mother in the person of linda lavin last seen here three 
years ago in neil simons broadway bound 
lavin plays rose the mother of stripper gypsy rose lee as a 
twitchy street fighter tough uncompromising and more than a tad 
neurotic 
its a thoroughly original even dangerous performance 
different from the portraits provided by the other formidable women 
ethel merman angela lansbury and tyne daly who have played the 
role on broadway over the last 30 years and its an amazing 
demonstration of what an actress who has thought out the role from 
a very specific point of view can do 
lavin is willing to let the audience dislike this rose as she 
forces daughters june and then louise into the show business 
careers she never had 
its a credit to lavins harsh performance that she refuses to 
soften the woman everything her rose wants she wants on her terms 
only whether its the love of that sweet candy salesman turned 
manager herbie or a career for her awkward alsoran daughter 
louise 
watch her grim determination as she prepares sweet little louise 
for her debut as a burlesque queen the concentration is awesome as 
rose contemplates finally making her daughter a star 
lavins fierceness extends to her singing the woman knows how 
to handle a theater song long before she was televisions 
alice she had a steady career in broadway musicals her 
roses turn is a frenzied cry for recognition for what she 
did 
whats amazing is that lavin manages to evoke a sense of pity 
for this woman making the ending moving and a bit teary as mother 
and daughter come to a sort of uneasy truce at the final curtain 
the rest of the cast has improved in the 10 months the show has 
been playing on broadway jonathan hadary remains the definitive 
herbie putting a human face on what is often a cipher of a 
character christen tassin is still hilariously horrific as baby 
june the worlds most obnoxious child star and crista moore has 
grown immeasurably in the title role of the ugly duckling who 
becomes a very sexy swan 
the score by jule styne and stephen sondheim is as brassy and 
classy as ever and arthur laurents book is a model of what 
musical comedy writing should be and now theres lavin mama rose 
has never been as unappealing and as fascinating 
 
falsettoland william finns musical about facing big city 
life in the age of aids keeps getting better and better in its 
recent transfer to offbroadways lucille lortel theater for an 
openended run the musical remains funny and poignant 
on repeated viewings two things stand out the melodic 
inventiveness of finns score and the rapidfire staging of 
director james lapine this is a musical that never stops for 70 
fast minutes the story of marvin and how he copes with his sons 
bar mitzvah and his lovers fatal illness never lets down 
musically or emotionally 
the cast headed by the superb michael rupert and stephen 
bogardus is now even more comfortable in the show its odd to 
think of a musical about aids as exhilarating and not depressing 
but falsettoland turns the act of growing up and coming to 
terms with oneself into an affecting piece of musical theater 
