<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
sept 1017 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the board of directors of the associated press 
has approved a general assessment increase of 39 percent for its 
1538 daily and weekly newspaper members and 5800 broadcast 
members effective jan 20 1991 
william j keating chairman of the ap board of directors and 
chairman and publisher of the cincinnati enquirer said the 
assessment increase in percentage terms was the lowest in three 
years 
mindful of the difficult times that confront much of the 
industry at this stage the board approved a rate increase that is 
well below the projected inflation rate for 1990 and 1991 
keating said 
the 39 percent increase will not cover all of the increases and 
new costs faced by ap ap will continue to meet the growing demands 
of the news industry through a vigorous cost control effort and by 
increasing nontraditional revenue sources keating said 
nontraditional sources now make up 24 percent of aps revenue 
eleven years ago that figure was 7 percent 
of the new money that ap needs to fund 1991 operations and 
continue to improve services only 31 cents of every dollar will 
come from the assessment increase keating said 
it is vital to all of us that our cooperative remain strong 
and able to meet the challenges in news coverage and technology 
keating said even as some members reduce their own activity to 
absorb the impact of a difficult year in the industry demands on 
the ap grow as we look to ap to do things that in a healthier 
time we might not have relied on ap to do 
the general assessment increase will be combined with another 
step in the phasein of the circulationbased newspaper formula for 
those members that have not reached their appropriate assessment 
level the 1991 assessment also will reflect any circulation 
changes at the member newspaper 
the assessment increase applies to all basic services for both 
newspapers and broadcasters and to all supplemental services except 
for the rates for financial market tables which are being adjusted 
downward in two steps in 1990 and 1991 to reflect savings achieved 
in producing computergenerated stock lists 
ap members will receive their new weekly assessment figures by 
early october keating said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
news and advertising employees at the new york 
post were to vote the evening of sept 17 on whether the nation 
oldest daily would live or die 
owner peter kalikow said if members of the newspaper guild did 
not agree to a fourday week meaning a loss of one days pay he 
would close immediately putting 960 people out of work the 
505000circulation paper is losing 27 million a year 
on sept 14 unions at the paper agreed to 19 million in 
concessions guild negotiators rejected kalikows offer 73 but 
the guild president endorsed it and decided to let the members 
decide 
the unions 352 editorial and advertising workers were voting on 
whether to accept a 20 percent pay cut and the elimination of 43 
jobs 
punctuated by a big question mark and a picture of the presses 
the front page headline sept 17 was possibly the 189yearold 
newspapers last will the post presses ever run again 
in a story inside editor jerry nachman was asked how he would 
feel if the post folded how did the captain of the titanic 
feel he asked 
i think we will get through this tonight because the 
alternative is unthinkable nachman said 
a 23year composing room veteran who declined to give his name 
as he arrived at work said its more than a job its part of 
your life its part of the life of the city 
if the post lives workers will get 20 percent of company stock 
and a representative on the board of directors union leaders said 
