<TEXT>
us employees of the reuters news agency 
authorized their union leadership to call a strike against the 
company the newspaper guild of new york said 
guild members voted by a larger than 201 margin for the 
authorization after contract talks that began nearly a year ago 
failed to result in an agreement the guild represents nearly 500 
employees including 150 journalists 
in a sept 10 news release the guild blamed the failing talks 
on reuters demands that it substantially raise the cost to 
employees for their health insurance while cutting maternity 
benefits and severance pay 
andrew nibley reuters editor responsible for north america and 
latin america refused to discuss details of the negotiations while 
they are in progress 
i would say that all major us corporations are dealing with 
the whole issue of spiraling health care costs and how they can be 
contained we think that our salaries are quite competitive and 
among the best in the industry he said 
i dont think a strike would be in anyones interest and i 
certainly hope it doesnt come to that he added 
the guild represents journalists technicians computer 
operators sales support staff customer service and clerical 
employees the last contract expired in february 
salaries at reuters range from 68075 to 84075 a week for 
reporters correspondents can make up to 99632 and salaries for 
technicians range from 69451 to 72751 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
united press international is closing bureaus 
in five states as part of a general staff realignment 
spokesman milt capps confirmed a report in the albuquerque 
nm tribune that bureaus in new mexico wyoming and montana 
would be closed he declined to say how many layoffs were involved 
capps also said upi had given notice to staffers in oneperson 
bureaus in grand rapids mich and bismarck nd 
he said the news service was expanding its stringer networks in 
the affected states and working on a number of joint ventures 
with people in the regions for additional coverage 
upi is taking quite a few steps this summer and fall to 
realign our staffing in the wake of our creation of a number of new 
autonomous editorial units he said the upshot is that 
virtually every bureau in the system worldwide is affected either 
by increases or decreases 
capps declined to discuss whether any future closures are 
planned or how many bureaus upi now operates in the united states 
last month he confirmed a washington post report that 31 upi 
reporters and editors were being laid off 
capps said there will be net increases in staffing in such areas 
as sports business and finance and emphasis on upis joint 
ventures with cable tvs financial news network states news 
service and financial world magazine 
we are developing what we think is a new role for upi after 83 
years which entails not only strong general news service but 
increased emphasis on focused news reports that can command a 
premium in the marketplace including media and corporate 
subscribers he said 
the bottom line is we can now say we have more people writing 
for upi across the board than a year ago he said 
</TEXT>
