<TEXT>
a federal judge dismissed a trademark 
infringement action brought by new kids on the block a pop group 
that sued usa today and star magazine for using their name in 
telephone surveys 
us district judge william j rea ruled sept 10 that the use 
of 900 toll numbers to gauge popularity of the group was a news 
gathering activity and therefore protected by the first amendment 
usa today asked readers who their favorite new kid was and star 
asked readers who they thought was the sexiest new kid each phone 
vote had a fee 
the new kids lawyer philip heller said he would appeal 
while we recognize the importance of the first amendment we 
disagree with judge reas application of it in this case heller 
said 
heller said 900 numbers are commercial services and the first 
amendment does not protect the use of anothers trademark and 
likeness to further commercial ventures even if a newspaper is 
involved he said 
he said the 900 polls competed with the groups own 900 hotline 
by using pictures of the singing group and their name 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a judge decided to allow reporters to take 
notes in his courtroom prompting philadelphias two daily 
newspapers to drop a legal challenge 
common pleas court judge eugene ej maier signed an order sept 
11 lifting the prohibition he earlier had said he felt notetaking 
could distract a jury and undercut the official record of a court 
proceeding 
after i had given further thought to it i dont think it 
offends me and we shouldnt keep on with it as long as we could 
control the matter in another way maier said 
he said he might ask reporters to sit in a part of the courtroom 
where jurors cannot see them 
philadelphia newspapers inc publisher of the philadelphia 
inquirer and the philadelphia daily news dropped its appeal of the 
ban which had been pending in state superior court 
the case arose when daily news reporter joseph p blake was 
ordered by a court officer last month to stop taking notes during a 
murder trial two inquirer reporters on separate days also were 
prevented from taking notes 
there has been a gut feeling that note taking should not be 
permitted the judge told an attorney for the newspapers 
according to a transcript of an aug 20 meeting in his chambers 
it may set up a method by which the official transcript can be 
tested or can be impeached should we say or at least 
contradicted maier said 
a jury could be swayed to give greater attention to some 
testimony rather than other testimony because a person took 
notes he said 
the newspapers said in their appeal the rule violated federal 
and state constitutional rights of reporters to cover criminal 
trials as surrogates for the public 
after lifting his ban the judge said he would continue to 
prohibit notetaking by members of the public who are not media 
representatives and would reserve the right to ban notetaking by 
reporters 
a judge is like the captain of a ship he said the judge 
has to control the courtroom the worst thing that can happen is 
that you dont have that control 
