<TEXT>
twenty newspapers have been selected as 
finalists in the associated press managing editors associations 
20th annual public service awards competition 
the finalists announced sept 13 were chosen from 122 entries 
79 from newspapers with more than 50000 circulation and 43 from 
newspapers with less than 50000 circulation 
one winner from each category will be announced in october at 
the apme convention in dallas 
finalists in the lessthan50000 category listed 
alphabetically by city are 
the albuquerque nm tribune for its series a price on their 
heads exposing the threat to elk eagles bear and other 
wildlife posed by animal traders trophy hunters and poachers 
the bismarck nd tribune for its investigation into the abuse 
of children placed in foster homes on the standing rock indian 
reservation 
the casper wyo startribune for its articles about the 
states lax regulation of insurance companies the reporting 
prompted the withdrawal of a gubernatorial candidate and the 
resignation of the state insurance commissioner 
the columbia missourian for a special report that concluded the 
public housing authority was not only the citys largest landlord 
but also the worst this and other coverage led to the resignation 
of the authoritys executive director and its chairman 
the livingston mont enterprise for comprehensive coverage by 
its fivemember news staff of the large and secretive church 
universal and triumphant and its damaging impact on an area 
adjacent to yellowstone national park 
the sun news of myrtle beach sc for providing detailed 
helpful responsible coverage of hurricane hugo even though its 
plant was disabled the newspaper organized a print and broadcast 
pool to report from the battered oceanfront 
the west county times of richmond calif for its series 
exposing safety and environmental violations at the san francisco 
bay areas six oil refineries as a result the state increased 
minimum fines for pollution from 1000 to 10000 
the salina kan journal for articles about use of excessive 
force by city police officers the report led to a state 
investigation and the retirement of the police chief 
the valley news dispatch of tarentum pa for a series that 
painstakingly documented the failure of local officials to collect 
more than 10 million in taxes owed to the areas 13 school 
districts 
the washington nc daily news for revealing that for eight 
years city officials had known cancercausing chemicals were in the 
tap water the disclosure resulted in a twomonth water ban an 
improved treatment system and state and federal reviews of water 
regulations 
finalists among newspapers with more than 50000 circulation 
are 
the albuquerque nm journal for discovering a link between 
the dietary supplement ltryptophan and a rare and sometimes deadly 
blood disorder ten days after the first story was published the 
federal government banned the sale of the supplement 
the chicago tribune for its series a dream in jeopardy a 
comprehensive examination of cutbacks in corporate pensions and 
health benefits and threats to the social security trust funds 
the des moines iowa register for a series about the rape of an 
iowa woman and how she coped with the emotional trauma and legal 
ordeal that followed the womans decision to be identified in the 
account touched off a national debate over whether to keep secret 
the names of rape victims 
the detroit news for uncovering the financial ties of the mayor 
and police chief to a former deputy chief at the center of a 
federal investigation into a secret police fund questionable 
practices by the officials were documented in spite of the city 
governments no comment policy when questioned by reporters 
the lexington ky heraldleader for its series cheating our 
children on political interference in the states public schools 
and the failure of local officials to collect property taxes owed 
to financially strapped school districts 
the courierjournal of louisville ky for a broad examination 
of the states publicschool crisis articles published over six 
months included four indepth series on flaws in the tax system 
the special problems in appalachia the need for preschool programs 
and ways to improve teaching 
the philadelphia inquirer for its series the blood brokers 
which lifted the veil from the unregulated multibilliondollar 
business of buying and selling blood dog kennels in pennsylvania 
were inspected more often than blood banks the series revealed 
the san jose calif mercury news for its comprehensive 
coverage of the oct 17 earthquake that devastated parts of 
northern california the day after the disaster and during the 
months that followed readers received exhaustive reporting vivid 
writing compelling photos and graphics and public service 
information 
the seattle postintelligencer for its report chemicals ride 
the food chain which revealed that truckers haul orange juice 
baby food and other cargo destined for human consumption after 
carrying toxic chemicals in the same tanks the disclosure resulted 
in a new state law prohibiting such practices and support for 
similar legislation in congress 
the blade of toledo ohio for its series the secret files of 
internal affairs based on a review of 200000 police 
disciplinary documents never before made public the sevenmonth 
project revealed that the department failed to prosecute officers 
for assault drunken driving and other crimes and that 98 percent 
of citizens complaints of police brutality were dismissed 
four newspapers were selected as finalists in the freedom of 
information award competition according to david hawpe editor of 
the courierjournal of louisville and chairman of the apme freedom 
of information committee the winner also will be announced at the 
apme convention 
the finalists are 
the detroit news for an investigation tracing payments from a 
secret detroit police fund through which more than 1 million in 
taxpayer money was said to be laundered the complex story touched 
on the activities of a deputy police chief mayor coleman young and 
others 
the fort lauderdale fla sunsentinel for a series on the 
state of floridas failure to impose adequate controls on care 
centers leading to deaths and injuries among such diverse groups 
as infants retarded adults and teenage criminals 
the daily reflector of greenville nc for revelations 
concerning the background of a candidate for superior court judge 
resulting in legislation changing state law to open the records of 
the north carolina judicial standards commission 
the hartford conn courant for an examination of the 
governments military recruiting system that suggested it promotes 
corruption undermines quality of the armed forces and costs 
taxpayers hundreds of millions of dollars annually 
