<TEXT>
it is difficult to view recessions as 
opportunities since everything seems to drop economic growth 
marketplace values jobs profits and perhaps most important hope 
in the future 
but there are people whose hopes rise while everything about 
them is falling they might not cheer the arrival of recession 
attended by its pain but they view it as a chance to participate 
in the future 
these people are true investors they recognize value are 
willing to take an informed risk and retain an innate faith in the 
economys ability to recover when it recovers so does the market 
value of wellchosen investments 
while recessions conceivably can continue for years as in the 
great depression of the 1930s the eight official economic 
recessions since world war ii have lasted an average of 12 months 
in the depths of these recessions stock prices have dived as 
much as 48 percent as in the recession that began in late 1973 
many of the bargains found in these sales subsequently rose to 
multiples of their purchase prices 
two things prevent people from taking advantage of such sales a 
lack of money since few people have the foresight opportunity or 
means to prepare for a recession and the courage to buy even 
among hardy investors 
the point has meaning at the moment since many economists who 
earlier had been fencesitting now are forecasting a recession over 
the next few months and into 1991 a mild one perhaps but enough 
to qualify 
a recession doesnt necessarily mean a sharp downturn in stock 
prices but that has been the experience prior to each of the 
recessions of the past 45 years there have been no exceptions 
prior to each recession stocks fell 
nobody has yet demonstrated that recession is certain but 
bargainhunting investors are getting ready in case 
gerald perritt editor of the newsletter blue chip values 
studied the experience of investors during those earlier recessions 
and found some bargainhunters 
first he found that during the typical bear market stock prices 
wound down over many months and that what at first appeared to be 
the bottom gave way to further price deterioration 
often he found bargainhunters jumped too early and regretted 
it as prices continued to fall a prolonged bear market he found 
is characterized by dead cat bounces or brief increases that 
merely lead to more declines 
as prices continue to decline he says even longterm investors 
begin to waver and dump their stocks in an attempt to salvage what 
remains of their portfolios usually this occurs near the ultimate 
bottom 
since nobody knows when a bounce is a dead cat or when a 
bottom is the ultimate perritt believes smart investors must 
follow rules of restraint 
based on his studies he believes the best time to buy in bear 
markets is three to six months after a recession begins since 
world war ii recessions have ranged from seven to 17 months with 
12 months the average 
in buying at midway in the recession bargainhunters would be 
relying on two factors favorable to prices the federal reserve 
will attemp to pump money into the economy and the extreme 
optimists will think of buying 
buying at midway however isnt easy the economic numbers will 
look bad the pessimists will be in their glory the news reports 
may sound foreboding and economic confidence may be shot 
by perritts reckoning however that is when you must make your 
move just as the stock market falls prior to recession it rises 
prior to recovery not to move decisively might mean losing out on 
the best buys in years 
</TEXT>
