<DOCNO> AP900917-0223 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
dick countryman practices squareinch gardening 
except for a few necessary paths his 30by50foot backyard is in 
nearly yearround production of vegetables and flowers 
plants in containers also fill most nooks and crannies and an 
enclosing 6foot wall supports climbers 
theres no road map wherever and whenever i have room to 
plant something i do it he says i dont believe in allowing 
ground to go fallow 
countryman feels his garden proves it isnt necessary to have a 
large plot to grow a constant supply of fresh vegetables and cut 
flowers hes been cultivating it more than 25 years now 64 and 
retired he thinks its a shame more people particularly retirees 
dont grow vegetables and flowers 
the big thing is to work at your own pace and avoid 
disappointment by first learning and then following the basic 
techniques he says he advises beginners to start small and 
dont try to do everything at once and estimates a 4foot by 
8foot vegetable garden is enough for one persons needs 
an august visitor counted at least 70 varieties of flowers 
about half of them in bloom there were more than 40 types of 
vegetables the vegetable count lumps as one type five varieties of 
tomatoes six of peppers three of cucumbers three of garlic 
three of onions and three of squash there were even 24 stalks of 
sweet corn 
i like pretty flowers i like nutritious fresh vegetables i 
like to experiment a lot of things i grow just to see if i can 
grow them countryman says by way of explanation 
his theory is to keep the ground in constant production 
its also moving the plants around crop rotation so you 
dont build up any diseases 
while there are perennials such as a strawberry patch most 
plants are pulled out as soon as they complete their cycle 
i might go in here with mutiplier onions or i might go in 
there with head lettuce or flowers or whatever he says 
the 100squarefoot strawberry bed always has been in the same 
place runners are used from time to time to replace older plants 
of course the bed produced berries ozark beauty and sequoia from 
december into july this year 
flowers are just as likely to follow vegetables as vegetables to 
follow flowers but the bulk of the vegetable production because 
of the desert climate and tripledigit summer temperatures in this 
phoenix suburb begins in the fall 
he has few worries about frost 
i can cut a fresh bouquet of flowers or gather fresh 
vegetables every day of the year he says 
while the intensive approach may seem unorthodox countrymans 
credentials are impeccable he retired recently as assistant 
director of the state horticultural and agricultural commission is 
a horticultural graduate from the university of arizona and is in 
frequent demand as a speaker on gardening subjects 
preparation of the planting bed is the secret he says do 
it right and youll have a reasonable amount of success 
for 100 square feet he covers it 4 inches deep with organic 
matter such as mulch and sprinkles two pounds of ammonium 
phosphate 16200 and five pounds of gypsum on top before turning 
it in twice the gypsum is used to counteract salt in local water 
gardeners in other areas may find lime or soil sulphur work better 
countryman seldom uses chemical pesticides finding that insects 
and diseases rarely bother healthy plants 
his planting beds are arranged so the watering bubbler system 
applies two inches uniformly every four days much of the year 
adequate water and healthy plants keep weeds to the minimum 
he says 
he has plants in more thsn 200 pots they range from miniature 
roses to chives to cucumbers to raspberries 
his potting mix formula is based on an ancient wheelbarrow with 
1 cubic foot capacity he starts with 4 inches of horse manure from 
a nearby riding stable and mixes this with a gallon container of 
perlite a gallon of vermiculite a cup of bonemeal two cups of 
gypsum and a gallon of any commercially sold potting mix 
the front yard is mostly flower beds and shrubs but it does 
include 100 square feet of lawn grass thats plenty of lawn to 
take care of he says 
 
editors note james walters worked for the ap as a reporter 
and editor from 1947 until he retired in 1984 
</TEXT>
