<TEXT>
with members of congress finally working hard to 
achieve budget cuts some of the very people who had urged them to 
do so are having second thoughts 
the very idea of cuts is so politically sensitive and 
economically involved that some of these people speak only in 
whispers but what those whispers convey is that now might not be 
the best time to cut anything but taxes 
events of the past several weeks have conspired to bring about 
this newer attitude events such as higher oil prices additional 
evidence of a decaying economy a squeeze on household budgets and 
a business credit crunch 
the weakening economy now worries some of these people more than 
continued budget overruns in spite of their having made the latter 
the biggest economic issue of the past year 
the latest job figures have added to the concern new job 
creation has fallen abruptly unemployment is up and monthly job 
gains in private industry so far this year hav been off nearly 50 
percent from the like period of 1989 
other reports show that the only parts of the economy still 
growing vibrantly are health care and state and local governments 
and each of these presents problems of its own inflation in health 
care and bureaucratic growth in government neither of them 
designed for a healthy economy 
but ask the whisperers is now the time to make cuts in 
government spending or even to hold it down if the private sector 
economy is withering what except government spending is available 
to give it a nudge 
besides it is said no matter what congress or the white house 
or anyone else wants spending isnt likely to come down when 
billions of dollars are being spent on the military action in the 
mideast 
in a announcement called straighttalk conference board 
economist gail fosler states that military and economic 
uncertainties combined with high tax burdens will prevent any 
meaningful action in slashing the deficit 
fosler comments that federal borrowing will surge over the 
next two years regardless of what the administration and congress 
do to bring down the deficit 
those who say congress shouldnt even try to make the effort 
arent declaring their positions nearly as boldly to do so would 
brand some of them as turncoats because all year long they have 
been advocating cuts 
but says one analyst of the economic scene as the 
grammrudman deadline of oct 1 draws near the weakening economy 
threatens to make these budget negotiations an academic 
excercise 
that comment comes from john wright of wright investors 
service who adds that clearly in its current fragile state the 
us economy can scarcely tolerate either higher taxes or 
acrosstheboard spending cuts 
but it can hardly afford higher interest rates either and until 
congress reaches some sort of agreement those rates are likely to 
remain high that much has been indicated by alan greenspan 
chairman of the federal reserve board 
not only does he remain committed to smaller budget deficits 
but he seems equally determined to forestall any drop in interest 
rates until congress reaches an agreement 
