<TEXT>
a national energy policy promoting the 
use of coal could have helped prevent the persian gulf crisis the 
united mine workers president said today at the convention marking 
the unions 100th anniversary 
the only reason characters like saddam hussein have any power 
at all is because of the oil they have oil we could have replaced 
years ago with coal mined in the united states and canada umw 
president richard trumka said 
aflcio president lane kirkland told the more than 1000 
delegates from the united states and canada that unions are on the 
verge of a breakthrough following the 1980s which he called a 
period of illusion excess and frustration 
kirkland urged support of a bill before congress that would bar 
employers from permanently replacing striking workers 
thats a basic right recognized in all but the most backward 
or repressive nations he said 
the umw rejoined the aflcio last year four decades after the 
famed umw president john l lewis pulled his union out 
other speakers scheduled to address the delegates include the 
rev jesse jackson and labor secretary elizabeth dole 
the celebration of the oncepowerful unions centennial is mixed 
with financial and legal concerns 
during the nineday meeting delegates will be asked to give the 
international executive board the umws governing body authority 
to close or merge the 21 local districts to help the union save 
money several of the largely autonomous districts are insolvent 
because of layoffs 
they also will decide whether to allow the governing body use of 
interest earnings from the 60 million strike fund to pay legal 
expenses and other costs associated with strikes currently the 
fund can be used only to pay benefits to strikers 
and the delegates will be asked to approve changes umw leaders 
say they need to deal with multinational corporations in the world 
coal market 
trumka and other union officials say the proposals will give the 
union the latitude to deal with coal companies that increasingly 
are owned by conglomerates such as exxon and du pont 
the convention at the opulent fontainebleau hotel comes as the 
umw struggles to overturn 52 million in fines levied by a virginia 
judge because of the 10month pittston strike in 1989 the union 
also faces more than 1 billion in lawsuits filed by companies 
idled by a fiveweek wildcat strike that began in sympathy with the 
pittston strikers 
the union declared victory in the bitter pittston strike but it 
was a costly win a financial disclosure form shows the unions net 
worth fell by 45 million in 1989 down to 126 million 
the umw formed in 1890 by the merger of two rival mine unions 
once held a firm grip on the nations energy needs as late as the 
1940s its 400000 members controlled 80 percent of the countrys 
coal production 
but the unions influence has declined in recent years beset by 
increased mechanization in the nations mines and a jump in the 
number of nonunion coal operations the umw has seen its working 
membership dip to about 70000 
</TEXT>
