<TEXT>
grain nd soybean futures prices turned lower 
after a mixed opening this morning on the chicago board of trade 
amid weak export demand and forecasts for mild temperatures in the 
midwest 
soybean futures opened higher after some private meteorologists 
predicted cold temperatures early next week in the midwest but the 
markets focus quickly turned to nearerterm factors including 
predictions for beneficial rain in the region later this week 
joel karlin grains analyst with research department inc in 
chicago said the markets also were responding to weak export 
demand across the board 
export business for all these markets is abysmal he said 
its been really hurting the wheat and corn and its starting to 
afflict the soybeans also 
the impending corn and soybean harvest is likely to increase 
selling interest karlin said 
in early trading wheat futures were 1 cent to 2 cents lower 
with the contract for delivery in september at 256 a bushel corn 
was cent to cents lower with september at 232 a bushel oats 
were unchanged to cent higher with december at 114 a bushel 
soybeans were 7 cents lower to 1 cents higher with september at 
618 a bushel 
livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the 
chicago mercantile exchange some pork belly futures leaped the 
permitted daily limit of 2 cents a pound in reaction to gains in 
the cash hog market and strong demand for pork 
live cattle were 43 cent to 70 cent higher with october at 
7915 cents a pound feeder cattle were 20 cent to 78 cent higher 
with september at 89 cents a pound live hogs were 15 cent to 128 
cents higher with october at 5315 cents a pound frozen pork 
bellies were 17 cents to 2 cents higher with february at 5665 
cents a pound 
cattle futures ended mixed on friday pork futures advanced 
