<TEXT>
general motors corp and the united auto workers 
reached tentative agreement early today on a new threeyear 
contract covering 300000 workers in 29 states 
im just delighted we got this contract settled without a 
disruption uaw president owen bieber said in announcing the 
agreement reached after a 41hour bargaining session between the 
union and the worlds no 1 automaker 
details of the agreement were to be outlined at a meeting this 
morning in suburban detroit of the unions 300member gm bargaining 
council made up of local union presidents and bargaining committee 
chairmen but that meeting broke up after only 15 minutes and was 
rescheduled for tuesday because the printing of the proposed 
contract had not been completed 
bieber said at a news conference before dawn that he was very 
very satisfied with the agreement on pensions and gm vice 
president alfred warren said the contract gives the company 
latitude to reduce its work force 
the detroit news reported today that the contract includes a 3 
percent raise the first year 3 percent lump sum payments the next 
two and retention of a requirement that gm hire one worker for 
every two who quit retire or die 
there had been speculation that gm would push hard to remove or 
alter the 1for2 policy and that the automaker wants to cut tens 
of thousands of hourly jobs and close up to four assembly plants to 
better compete with the japanese 
the big three automakers lost about 6 percentage points in us 
market share during the 1980s while the japanese gained the same 
amount 
if approved by the uaw council the contract would be sent to 
the rank and file for ratification a process expected to be 
completed by the end of the month 
as he arrived for this mornings meeting tom robinson 
president of local 549 in mansfield ohio who helped negotiate the 
settlement said only that it met all the goals we came down here 
to meet 
earl perry of local 2188 in fitzgerald ga was more cautious 
we still have to get through this one he said referring to 
the sincerescheduled bargaining council meeting 
the uaws old threeyear contract with gm expired at midnight 
friday but both sides agreed to extend its terms while talks 
continued 
uaw contracts with ford motor co and chrysler corp also ran 
out at the same time but the union put talks with ford and 
chrysler on hold so that it could concentrate on gm and use that 
pact as a model for the other automakers 
bieber and warren said the new agreement could be tailored to 
ford and chrysler 
the unions contracts with the big three automakers cover more 
than 450000 active workers this year was the first time in 11 
years that uaw contracts with each of the big three ran out at the 
same time 
the last time the uaw struck gm was in 1984 that strike lasted 
a week and ultimately involved about 25 gm facilities nationwide 
meanwhile talks continued in toronto between the canadian auto 
workers union and ford of canada the caws 12800 members at ford 
of canada struck early saturday after talks broke off 
negotiations were held later saturday and resumed sunday no 
plants involved operate on weekends so any strike impact wont be 
felt until today if the strike continued us ford plants that 
use parts made in canada would be affected 
bieber whose unions 15million membership dropped by a third 
largely because of the shrinking us auto industry said he 
expected the tentative agreement would get a warm reception by the 
bargaining council suffice it to say at this point they will be 
pleased with what we have to say he said 
warren said the talks were some of the most difficult 
bargaining ever between gm and the union but warren and bieber 
were upbeat about the prospects for changing labor relations 
between the company and union 
we feel that the spirit we developed during the negotiations 
the relationship we built with the new leadership of the united 
automobile workers bodes well for general motors for the customer 
the marketplace and the united automobile workers warren said 
the average hourly wage with cost of living adjustments for gm 
workers is about 1575 under the 1987 agreement fringe benefits 
particularly health care costs boost that to nearly 30 per hour 
the company has said 
at ford the figure is about 31 per hour and chryslers was 
just more than 33 
some of the fringe benefits include pension matters which was a 
hot topic going into the talks there was a strong movement within 
the uaw to include costofliving adjustments keyed to the 
inflation rate 
</TEXT>
