<TEXT>
the american stock exchange announced monday it 
was planning a trading facility in hawaii in an attempt to link 
us and pacific stock and options markets during the tokyo 
business day 
the exchange set an 18month timetable to develop a business 
plan and negotiate with american and far east financial 
institutions for joint ventures that would be necessary to open a 
trading facility in hawaii 
as global financial markets evolve in the 1990s there will be 
the increasing demand for foreign securities by investors in both 
the us and pacific rim countries american stock exchange 
chairman james r jones said 
the business day in hawaii overlaps trading in new york and 
tokyo the worlds two key financial markets 
the amex is the secondlargest us exchange behind the new york 
stock exchange it recently has sought to expand into new products 
and technologies that tie into the gloablization of world markets 
the hawaii venture is being planned with the economic 
development corp of honolulu a nonprofit organization under 
contract to the state it represents the honolulu financial center 
task force which is lobbying for a financial center in hawaii 
the amex said in a statement that a variety of financial 
products could be offered in a hawaii trading facility including 
some not currently sold in asian markets 
it said the success of a honolulu facility would depend on 
attracting investment order flow from japan and other asian 
countries the statement said hawaii is a hub for a new 
transpacific fiber optic cable system and has proximity to more 
than a dozen satellites for data transmission 
</TEXT>
