with strong gains in california and new mexico 
the number of working oil and natural gas rigs in the united states 
rose again this week climbing by 21 to 1060 baker hughes inc 
reported monday 
this weeks tally reflected a smaller increase than the 26 rigs 
added a week ago despite gains of 17 rigs in new mexico and 13 in 
california 
ic kerridge a vice president and economist at baker hughes 
which has been making the survey ince 1940 said the middle east 
situation appeared not to be affecting the count much this week 
a week ago industry watchers credited the 26rig jump to rising 
oil prices triggered by the middle east crisis 
the count a year ago was 965 baker hughes said 
in canada the rig count of 117 represented a jump of 20 a year 
ago the canadian tally was 100 
kerridge speculated the new mexico increase was due to drillers 
working coal seam wells in the northwest part of the state the 
wells produce methane gas from coal deposits and a federal subsidy 
for such wells expires at the end of the year he said 
the california increase followed a previous decline and 
reflected an adjustment in the market kerridge said 
among other major oilproducing states colorado added four 
rigs while oklahoma was up two kansas north dakota and 
pennsylvania each declined by three while ohio lost two and 
michigan one louisiana texas and wyoming were unchanged 
the houstonbased oil toolmakers rig count a widely watched 
index of drilling activity represents the number of rigs actively 
exploring for oil not those producing oil 
at the height of the oil boom in december 1981 the rig count 
reached a peak of 4500 but the rig count plunged to a low of 663 
after oil prices collapsed in the summer of 1986 
