<TEXT>
chrysler corp chairman lee iacocca blames 
himself for the no 3 us automakers deterioration in recent 
years particularly a botched effort to diversify and a failure to 
create more popular cars 
im confessing my sins here iacocca was quoted as telling 
the wall street journal in an interview published monday 
iacocca who turns 66 next month is famous for salvaging 
chrysler from nearbankruptcy at the end of the 1970s in what 
became a nowlegendary comeback 
but under iacocca chrysler has weakened again hurt by vigorous 
competition particularly from imports 
chryslers sales have dropped nearly 17 percent this year vs an 
industrywide decline of 5 percent 
by some estimates chrysler will conclude 1990 as the fifth 
biggest seller of cars in the united states behind japans honda 
motor co and toyota motor corp as well as its historical us 
rivals general motors corp and ford motor co 
during a twohour interview in his highland park mich 
headquarters iacocca said he was determined to lead chrysler 
through a second comeback 
his major failing he was quoted as saying was trying to 
diversify chrysler by expanding into the aerospace and defense 
businesses a strategy that gm and ford also undertook 
he said chryslers effort led to the formation of a holding 
company that added a layer of bureaucracy and diverted the company 
from its main business of producing new vehicles 
chrysler is now shedding its nonauto businesses in an attempt 
to refocus on cars but its current models are still largely 
derived from the 10yearold kcar 
if i made a mistake it was following other companies and 
maybe those were grandiose schemes iacocca said we didnt need 
a holding company thats what made us topheavy 
to shore up its finances chrysler has undertaken a largescale 
cost reduction program including the closing of one third of its 
assembly plants in the past three years iacocca has ordered 25 
billion in reductions to be made by the middle of next year 
