<TEXT>
about 25000 shipping industry workers 
went on strike monday in the black sea port of constanta bringing 
most of romanias sea shipping to a halt 
the strike included ship workers navigators dock workers and 
drivers employed by area transport services 
strikers claim a government program announced in june promising 
higher wages better working conditions and speedy decentralization 
of industry was being impeded by government bureaucrats and local 
officials 
adrian tanase an attorney and union leader of the port workers 
said the strike would continue indefinitely he said the 
navigators union sent a telegram monday telling all romanian ships 
worldwide to stop loading or unloading cargo 
the transport ministry said the walkout was unjustified because 
most of the demands have been discussed with the government and are 
being studied by authorities 
the ministry said that among the original demands made by the 
unions in talks with government last week were relaxed import 
rights for seamen to bring in cars video equipment and other 
luxury goods tax free into romania 
president ion iliescu met with several union leaders monday 
the main unions involved in the strike demanded the dismissal 
and punishment of administrators who have not been able to carry 
out the governments promises to workers 
port workers demanded that the port be turned over to private 
hands that safety standards be adhered to and that customs laws be 
changed to make it easier to import goods 
the unions also demanded a share of an estimated 215 million 
worth of property formerly belonging to the prerevolutionary trade 
union confederation in romania which was reorganized shortly after 
the revolution 
the striking unions which have sprung up since and are not 
