<DOCNO> AP900917-0269 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
eastman kodak co unveiled a product that 
allows snapshots to be stored on compact discs and played back on 
televisions 
the kodak photo cd system digitally stores images from negatives 
or slides on compact discs the pictures can then be shown on 
ordinary television or computer screens with a photo cd player that 
also plays audio cds 
this is the answer for consumers who have wanted both the 
astonishing quality of 35 millimeter photography and the 
convenience of digital storage display and manipulation users can 
enjoy traditional photographic quality and view their pictures on 
tv kodak chairman and chief executive kay whitmore said in a 
statement 
the system will not be available until 1992 kodak said it made 
the announcement to give other manufacturers time to develop 
licensed products and software 
kodak introduced the photo cd at a news conference in tokyo 
tuesday morning the company planned news conferences later in the 
day in london new york and rochester 
to use the system film is first processed conventionally into 
negatives or slides each picture is then scanned and transferred 
into digital form and the compressed digital image is written to a 
compact disc 
photo customers bringing film in to a photofinisher will have 
the option of ordering a photo cd along with their prints and 
negatives or slides kodak said unfilled discs can be returned to 
have more images added creating electronic albums of up to 100 
pictures 
the digital pictures have the same resolution and color quality 
as a film image according to kodak officials because that 
resolution is 16 times greater than a regular television and four 
times greater than high definition television formats the 
technology will not become obsolete for a long time spokesman paul 
allen said 
we believe this will set the standard for many years to 
come allen said 
the cd player allows viewers to manipulate the picture on the 
television screen by zooming in cropping a picture or shuffling 
the order 
the company anticipates the photo cd player will take the place 
of the slide projector for group viewing of photographs allen 
said 
the system was developed jointly with dutch consumer electronics 
company nv philips which owns most cd patents the photo cd 
players will be manufactured by philips and will play either 
photographic or audio cds kodak will manufacture the goldcolored 
photographic cds each capable of holding up to 100 images 
the photo cd player is expected to cost less than 500 and a 
photo cd less than 20 
the photofinishing system consists of a highresolution film 
scanner made by kodak a computer work station and image processing 
software a philipsmade discwriter and kodak thermal printer the 
processing system is expected to cost less than 100000 and will 
be targeted at photofinishers and possibly even minilabs allen 
said 
the discs which will be manufactured in rochester are 
compatible with computer cd1 and cd rom xa readers kodak 
officials said they expect software to be developed that will make 
the system compatible with most computers 
the company expects other uses for the system to emerge in 
desktop publishing and other fields officials said 
</TEXT>
